Question Text: Given the following URI https://courses.examsdigest.com/ccna, which part is the hostname?
Choices:
a. https
b. courses
c. courses.examsdigest.com
d. examsdigest.com
e. examsdigest.com/ccna
LLM Explanation: The hostname in the given URI is 'courses.examsdigest.com'. The hostname is the part of the URI that identifies the network host or server where the resource is located. It comes after the scheme (https://) and before the path (/ccna) in the URI structure.
URLs: ['RFC 3986: Uniform Resource Identifier (URI): Generic Syntax - https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986', 'Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 26: Fundamentals of IP Version 6']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 443?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure) uses port 443 by default. HTTPS is the secure version of HTTP, which uses SSL/TLS for encryption and authentication. HTTP uses port 80, SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) uses port 25, and SSH (Secure Shell) uses port 22.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 3: Fundamentals of WANs and IP Routing']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 80?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) uses port 80 by default. It is the protocol used for transmitting web pages and other web content over the internet. HTTPS uses port 443, SMTP uses port 25, and SSH uses port 22.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'Cisco Networking Academy: CCNA Routing and Switching Essentials v6.0 - Chapter 7: Access Control Lists']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 25?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) is the protocol used for sending email messages between servers. It uses port 25 by default. HTTP uses port 80, HTTPS uses port 443, and SSH uses port 22.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Cisco Press)', 'https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 22?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SSH (Secure Shell) is a network protocol that uses port 22 by default for secure remote login and other secure network services over an unsecured network. HTTPS uses port 443, HTTP uses port 80, and SMTP uses port 25.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'SSH.com: SSH Port - Port 22: https://www.ssh.com/academy/ssh/port']

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the SNMP protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: The Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) uses UDP port 161 for sending and receiving requests between managers and agents. Port 161 is the standard port for SNMP network management traffic.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'RFC 1157 - Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP): https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1157']

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the POP3 protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: POP3 (Post Office Protocol version 3) uses TCP port 110 for unencrypted communication. It is a standard protocol used by email clients to retrieve email messages from a remote server.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'RFC 1939 - Post Office Protocol - Version 3: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1939']

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the DNS protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: The DNS protocol uses port 53 for its communication. DNS is used to translate domain names to IP addresses. When a client needs to resolve a domain name, it sends a DNS query to a DNS server using UDP port 53. The DNS server then responds back with the corresponding IP address, also using port 53.
URLs: ['IETF RFC 1035 - Domain Names - Implementation and Specification: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1035', 'Cisco Press - CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 21: DNS and DHCP']

Question Text: Which of the following options are things that a standard IP ACL could be configured to do? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. Match the exact source IP address
b. Match all IP addresses in a subnet with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
c. Match IP addresses 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
d. Match only the packet’s destination IP address
LLM Explanation: A standard IP access control list (ACL) can match the exact source IP address of a packet, as well as all IP addresses in a subnet using wildcard masking with a single access-list command. It cannot match a specific range of IP addresses like 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with one command. Standard IP ACLs also only examine the source IP address of packets, not the destination IP address.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: IP Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: One of the differences between named and numbered ACLs is that named ACLS using ACL subcommands, not global commands, to define the action and matching parameters.
Choices:
a. TRUE
b. FALSE
LLM Explanation: The statement is true. Named ACLs use ACL subcommands under the named ACL to define the action (permit or deny) and matching parameters (source IP, destination IP, protocol, etc.). In contrast, numbered ACLs use global configuration commands to define the action and matching parameters directly under the global configuration mode.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']

Question Text: Given the following fields, which of those cannot be compared on an extended IP ACL?
Choices:
a. Application protocol
b. Destination IP address
c. Source IP address
d. URL
e. TOS Byte
LLM Explanation: Extended IP access control lists (ACLs) can filter based on source and destination IP addresses, IP protocol number, source and destination ports for TCP/UDP traffic, and differentiated services code point (DSCP) values (part of the TOS byte). However, they cannot filter based on application-layer information like URLs. To filter web traffic by URL, a more advanced feature like a web content filter would need to be used.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: IP Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #1: Permit packets from 186.33.2.3
ACL command #1: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3
b. access-list 1 deny 186.33.2.3
c. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.0
d. access-list 1 deny 186.33.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a' because the access-list command should use 'permit' to allow packets from the specific IP address 186.33.2.3. The other options are incorrect because they either use 'deny' which would block the packets, or they specify a different IP address or network that does not match the given criteria.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #2: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets
ACL command #2: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 1 permit 57.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 deny 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a'. The ACL command 'access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255' matches the given criteria to permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets. The wildcard mask '0.0.0.255' allows any value in the last octet, effectively matching all hosts with 56.57.2 in the first three octets.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 14: ACL Concepts', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #3: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets
ACL command #3: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255
b. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.255.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.58.0.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'b' because the wildcard mask '0.0.255.255' matches the first two octets (56.57) exactly while allowing any value in the last two octets. This will permit packets from hosts with IP addresses starting with 56.57.x.x. Option 'a' uses an incorrect wildcard mask that would match any IP in the range 56.x.x.x. Option 'c' has the wrong third octet value (58 instead of 57). Option 'd' uses a wildcard mask of all zeros which would only match the exact IP 56.57.0.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'Cisco Documentation: Configure IP Access Control Lists - https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #4: Permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5, sent to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24
ACL command #4: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq 23
b. access-list 101 permit any any
c. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
d. access-list 101 deny tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is c. The access-list command should permit TCP traffic from the specific host 65.5.5.5 to the subnet 65.5.6.0/24 using the www (HTTP) port. Option a uses the wrong port number 23 (Telnet). Option b permits all traffic, which is too broad. Option d denies the traffic instead of permitting it.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Access Control Lists', 'Cisco IOS Security Configuration Guide, Release 12.4, Configuring IP Access Lists']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #5: Permit any and every IPv4 packet
ACL command #5: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit ip any any
b. access-list 101 deny ip any any
c. access-list 101 permit ip 0.0.0.0 any
d. access-list 101 permit ip any 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a. access-list 101 permit ip any any'. This extended ACL command permits any and every IPv4 packet as specified in the criteria. The 'any' keyword is used for both the source and destination, effectively matching all IPv4 traffic.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 2, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']

Question Text: Which of the following commands display the configuration of an IPv4 ACL, including line numbers? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. show running-config
b. show startup-config
c. show ip access-lists
d. show access-lists
LLM Explanation: The 'show ip access-lists' and 'show access-lists' commands are used to display the configuration of IPv4 ACLs, including the line numbers. The 'show running-config' and 'show startup-config' commands display the entire running configuration and startup configuration of the device respectively, which may include ACLs but not specifically with line numbers.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, 2020', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/xe-16-10/sec-data-acl-xe-16-10-book/sec-acl-show-commands.html']

Question Text: Type the access-list command that permits all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24. Use the ACL number 50 for the ACL rule.
Choices:
a. access-list 50 permit 14.15.17.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 50 deny 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.255.255.255
d. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit all packets from the 14.15.16.0/24 subnet is 'access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255'. The ACL number 50 is used as specified. The subnet 14.15.16.0 is the source address, and the wildcard mask 0.0.0.255 matches all hosts within that /24 subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: ACLs and Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Given the following access-list command access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255, choose the exact range of IP addresses, matched by the command.
LLM Explanation: The access-list command 'access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255' matches the IP address range 192.168.4.0 - 192.168.4.255. The first part '192.168.4.0' specifies the network address, and the second part '0.0.0.255' is the wildcard mask. A wildcard mask of '0.0.0.255' means that the last octet can be any value from 0 to 255, while the first three octets must match exactly. Therefore, the range matched by this command is 192.168.4.0 through 192.168.4.255.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: The range of valid ACL numbers for standard numbered IP ACLs is:
LLM Explanation: The valid range for standard numbered IP access control lists (ACLs) is 1-99 and 1300-1999. The range 1-99 is used for standard IP ACLs, while the range 1300-1999 is an expanded range also usable for standard IP ACLs. The other ranges mentioned in the choices are not valid for standard numbered IP ACLs.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
The ACL 55 on R1 has four statements, in the following order, with address and wildcard mask values as follows:
1. 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255
2. 20.20.0.0 0.0.255.255
3. 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255
4. 2.2.2.0 0.0.0.255
If a router tried to match a packet sourced from IP address 20.20.20.20 using this ACL, which ACL statement does a router consider the packet to have matched?
Choices:
a. First statement
b. Second statement
c. Third statement
d. Forth statement
e. Implied deny at the end of the ACL
LLM Explanation: The router will match the packet to the most specific ACL statement. In this case, the third statement '20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255' is the most specific match for the source IP 20.20.20.20. The first and second statements are less specific matches, while the fourth statement does not match at all. The implied deny at the end is only considered if no other statements match.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3 and a destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 28
b. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny tcp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 25 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access-list command to deny packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3, and a destination port equal to 25 is: 'access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25'. This matches the syntax and parameters specified in the question.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Security Command Reference: access-list (IP extended) command', 'Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide Library, Chapter 12: Access Control Lists']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, a source IP address 30.3.3.3 and a source port greater than 10455, any destination IP address 30.3.3.3 with destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 30
b. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 25 any eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.0.0.0 gt 10455 any eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is d. The access list entry 'access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25' matches the given criteria: - It denies UDP packets (deny udp) - From source IP 30.3.3.3 (host 30.3.3.3)  - With source port greater than 10455 (gt 10455) - To any destination IP (any) - With destination port equal to 25 (eq 25) The other options have incorrect parameters such as wrong source IP (30.0.0.0 in option c), wrong destination port (eq 30 in option a), or wrong source port (gt 25 in option b) which do not match the question.
URLs: ['https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Choose the wildcard mask that matches all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0, and mask 255.255.255.0.
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. In this case, the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0, so the wildcard mask would be 0.0.0.255. This wildcard mask will match all IP addresses in the 46.45.44.0/24 subnet.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/26448-ACLsamples.html']
